## 4. Numerical Integration: Riemann Sums

**The problem:** Compute ∫f(x)dx from `a` to `b` when `f` has no elementary antiderivative, or when you only have sample points. **Idea:** Approximate the area with rectangles (or trapezoids, or parabolas).

**Left Riemann sum:** Divide `[a, b]` into `n` subintervals of width `Δx = (b - a)/n`. The area of each rectangle is `f(xᵢ) · Δx`, where `xᵢ` is the left endpoint.

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print the approximate integral -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define (riemann-left f a b n)
  (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
    (define (sum i acc)
      (if (>= i n)
          acc
          (let ((x (+ a (* i dx))))
            (sum (+ i 1) (+ acc (* (f x) dx))))))
    (sum 0 0)))

(riemann-left f 0 1 10)
```

[VISUAL: print the result: `0.285`. The true value of ∫₀¹ x² dx = 1/3 ≈ 0.333, so the left sum underestimates.]

**Right Riemann sum:** Use the right endpoint of each subinterval.

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print the approximate integral -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define (riemann-right f a b n)
  (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
    (define (sum i acc)
      (if (>= i n)
          acc
          (let ((x (+ a (* (+ i 1) dx))))
            (sum (+ i 1) (+ acc (* (f x) dx))))))
    (sum 0 0)))

(riemann-right f 0 1 10)
```

[VISUAL: print the result: `0.385`. The right sum overestimates (because `f` is increasing).]

**Midpoint Riemann sum:** Use the midpoint of each subinterval—usually more accurate than left or right.

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print the approximate integral -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define (riemann-midpoint f a b n)
  (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
    (define (sum i acc)
      (if (>= i n)
          acc
          (let ((x (+ a (* (+ i 0.5) dx))))
            (sum (+ i 1) (+ acc (* (f x) dx))))))
    (sum 0 0)))

(riemann-midpoint f 0 1 10)
```

[VISUAL: print the result: `0.3325`. Much closer to the true value 1/3!]

**Convergence as n increases:**

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print a table of (n, estimate) pairs -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define (riemann-midpoint f a b n)
  (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
    (define (sum i acc)
      (if (>= i n)
          acc
          (let ((x (+ a (* (+ i 0.5) dx))))
            (sum (+ i 1) (+ acc (* (f x) dx))))))
    (sum 0 0)))

(map (lambda (n) (list n (riemann-midpoint f 0 1 n)))
     '(10 20 50 100 200))
```

[VISUAL: print the table: `((10 0.3325) (20 0.333125) (50 0.333320) (100 0.333330) (200 0.333332))`. As n → ∞, the estimate → 1/3.]

---

## 5. Numerical Integration: Trapezoidal Rule

**The idea:** Instead of rectangles, use *trapezoids*—connect `(xᵢ, f(xᵢ))` and `(xᵢ₊₁, f(xᵢ₊₁))` with a straight line. The area of each trapezoid is `(f(xᵢ) + f(xᵢ₊₁))/2 · Δx`.

**The formula:**
```
∫ₐᵇ f(x) dx ≈ (Δx/2) · [f(x₀) + 2f(x₁) + 2f(x₂) + ... + 2f(xₙ₋₁) + f(xₙ)]
```

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print the approximate integral -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define (trapezoid f a b n)
  (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
    (define (sum i acc)
      (if (> i n)
          acc
          (let ((x (+ a (* i dx))))
            (sum (+ i 1)
                 (+ acc (* (if (or (= i 0) (= i n)) 1 2)
                           (f x)))))))
    (* (/ dx 2) (sum 0 0))))

(trapezoid f 0 1 10)
```

[VISUAL: print the result: `0.335`. The trapezoidal rule splits the difference between left and right sums—more accurate than either alone.]

**Convergence:**

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print a table of (n, estimate) pairs -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define (trapezoid f a b n)
  (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
    (define (sum i acc)
      (if (> i n)
          acc
          (let ((x (+ a (* i dx))))
            (sum (+ i 1)
                 (+ acc (* (if (or (= i 0) (= i n)) 1 2)
                           (f x)))))))
    (* (/ dx 2) (sum 0 0))))

(map (lambda (n) (list n (trapezoid f 0 1 n)))
     '(10 20 50 100 200))
```

[VISUAL: print the table: `((10 0.335) (20 0.33375) (50 0.333340) (100 0.333335) (200 0.333333))`. Quadratic convergence—error decreases by 1/4 when n doubles.]

**Integrate sin(x) from 0 to π:**

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print the approximate integral and compare to exact value 2 -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (geom/sin x))

(define (trapezoid f a b n)
  (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
    (define (sum i acc)
      (if (> i n)
          acc
          (let ((x (+ a (* i dx))))
            (sum (+ i 1)
                 (+ acc (* (if (or (= i 0) (= i n)) 1 2)
                           (f x)))))))
    (* (/ dx 2) (sum 0 0))))

(list 'estimate (trapezoid f 0 const/pi 20)
      'exact 2.0)
```

[VISUAL: print `(estimate 1.9998... exact 2.0)`. The trapezoidal rule is very accurate for smooth functions.]

