## 6. Numerical Integration: Simpson's Rule

**The idea:** Instead of straight lines (trapezoids), fit a *parabola* through each triplet of points. Simpson's rule is exact for polynomials up to degree 3, and converges faster than the trapezoidal rule.

**The formula (requires n even):**
```
∫ₐᵇ f(x) dx ≈ (Δx/3) · [f(x₀) + 4f(x₁) + 2f(x₂) + 4f(x₃) + ... + 4f(xₙ₋₁) + f(xₙ)]
```
(Coefficients alternate 4, 2, 4, 2, ..., with 1 at the endpoints.)

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print the approximate integral -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define (simpson f a b n)
  (if (not (= (modulo n 2) 0))
      (list 'error 'n-must-be-even)
      (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
        (define (sum i acc)
          (if (> i n)
              acc
              (let ((x (+ a (* i dx)))
                    (coeff (cond ((or (= i 0) (= i n)) 1)
                                 ((= (modulo i 2) 1) 4)
                                 (else 2))))
                (sum (+ i 1) (+ acc (* coeff (f x)))))))
        (* (/ dx 3) (sum 0 0)))))

(simpson f 0 1 10)
```

[VISUAL: print the result: `0.33333333333...`. Simpson's rule is exact for quadratics—it returns exactly 1/3!]

**Integrate sin(x) from 0 to π:**

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print the approximate integral -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (geom/sin x))

(define (simpson f a b n)
  (if (not (= (modulo n 2) 0))
      (list 'error 'n-must-be-even)
      (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
        (define (sum i acc)
          (if (> i n)
              acc
              (let ((x (+ a (* i dx)))
                    (coeff (cond ((or (= i 0) (= i n)) 1)
                                 ((= (modulo i 2) 1) 4)
                                 (else 2))))
                (sum (+ i 1) (+ acc (* coeff (f x)))))))
        (* (/ dx 3) (sum 0 0)))))

(list 'simpson (simpson f 0 const/pi 20)
      'exact 2.0)
```

[VISUAL: print `(simpson 2.0000000... exact 2.0)`. Machine-precision accuracy with just 20 subintervals!]

**Convergence comparison:**

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print a table comparing trapezoid and Simpson for increasing n -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x x))

(define (trapezoid f a b n)
  (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
    (define (sum i acc)
      (if (> i n)
          acc
          (let ((x (+ a (* i dx))))
            (sum (+ i 1)
                 (+ acc (* (if (or (= i 0) (= i n)) 1 2)
                           (f x)))))))
    (* (/ dx 2) (sum 0 0))))

(define (simpson f a b n)
  (if (not (= (modulo n 2) 0))
      (list 'error 'n-must-be-even)
      (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
        (define (sum i acc)
          (if (> i n)
              acc
              (let ((x (+ a (* i dx)))
                    (coeff (cond ((or (= i 0) (= i n)) 1)
                                 ((= (modulo i 2) 1) 4)
                                 (else 2))))
                (sum (+ i 1) (+ acc (* coeff (f x)))))))
        (* (/ dx 3) (sum 0 0)))))

(map (lambda (n) (list n 
                      (trapezoid f 0 1 n) 
                      (simpson f 0 1 n)))
     '(10 20 40))
```

[VISUAL: print the table: `((10 0.2502... 0.25000...) (20 0.2500625 0.25000...) (40 0.250015... 0.25000...))`. Simpson converges much faster—quartic error vs. quadratic for trapezoid. Exact value: ∫₀¹ x³ dx = 1/4.]

