## 7. Adaptive Quadrature

**The problem:** Fixed-grid methods (trapezoid, Simpson) waste effort on smooth regions and miss detail in wiggly regions. **Adaptive quadrature** uses *more* subintervals where the function changes rapidly, and *fewer* where it's smooth.

**The strategy:** Estimate the integral over `[a, b]` with a coarse rule (say, n subintervals) and a fine rule (2n subintervals). If the two estimates agree to within tolerance, accept the fine estimate. Otherwise, split `[a, b]` at the midpoint and recurse on each half.

**A simple adaptive Simpson's rule:**

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print the integral and the number of function evaluations -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (geom/sin x))

(define (simpson-interval f a b)
  (let ((h (/ (- b a) 2))
        (mid (/ (+ a b) 2)))
    (* (/ h 3)
       (+ (f a)
          (* 4 (f mid))
          (f b)))))

(define eval-count 0)

(define (f-counted x)
  (set! eval-count (+ eval-count 1))
  (f x))

(define (adaptive-simpson f a b tol)
  (define (helper a b whole)
    (let* ((mid (/ (+ a b) 2))
           (left (simpson-interval f a mid))
           (right (simpson-interval f mid b))
           (sum (+ left right)))
      (if (< (abs (- sum whole)) (* 15 tol))
          sum
          (+ (helper a mid left)
             (helper mid b right)))))
  (helper a b (simpson-interval f a b)))

(set! eval-count 0)
(let ((result (adaptive-simpson f-counted 0 const/pi 1e-6)))
  (list 'integral result 'evals eval-count))
```

[VISUAL: print `(integral 2.000000... evals 25)`. Adaptive quadrature achieves high accuracy with far fewer evaluations than a fixed grid would need.]

**Integrate a function with a sharp peak:**

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, compare adaptive vs. fixed Simpson -->

```scheme
(define (f x) (math/exp (- (* x x))))

(define (simpson-interval f a b)
  (let ((h (/ (- b a) 2))
        (mid (/ (+ a b) 2)))
    (* (/ h 3)
       (+ (f a)
          (* 4 (f mid))
          (f b)))))

(define (adaptive-simpson f a b tol)
  (define (helper a b whole)
    (let* ((mid (/ (+ a b) 2))
           (left (simpson-interval f a mid))
           (right (simpson-interval f mid b))
           (sum (+ left right)))
      (if (< (abs (- sum whole)) (* 15 tol))
          sum
          (+ (helper a mid left)
             (helper mid b right)))))
  (helper a b (simpson-interval f a b)))

(define (simpson f a b n)
  (if (not (= (modulo n 2) 0))
      (list 'error 'n-must-be-even)
      (let ((dx (/ (- b a) n)))
        (define (sum i acc)
          (if (> i n)
              acc
              (let ((x (+ a (* i dx)))
                    (coeff (cond ((or (= i 0) (= i n)) 1)
                                 ((= (modulo i 2) 1) 4)
                                 (else 2))))
                (sum (+ i 1) (+ acc (* coeff (f x)))))))
        (* (/ dx 3) (sum 0 0)))))

(list 'adaptive (adaptive-simpson f -3 3 1e-6)
      'fixed-20 (simpson f -3 3 20))
```

[VISUAL: print `(adaptive 1.7724... fixed-20 1.7723...)`. The adaptive method automatically concentrates samples near x=0 where the Gaussian peak is sharpest.]

